M-1600-HU-0662	Vázquez de Espinosa, Antonio		Spanish	The author, on p. 469, states that the ash from the eruption spread over 200 leagues and reached the ships that were sailing. Vázquez de Espinosa claims that at the time of writing there was still a lot of ash for more than 150 leagues, which he himself had seen. According to witnesses, many incandescent pumice stones fell into the Tambo river and ended up devastating farms and their livestock. When the river flowed into the sea, it ended up cooking the fish and, according to the author, it was thanks to God that their corpses did not cause a plague. The ash rain lasted seven days, prevented the sun from being seen and caused many houses to fall and burn down. The earth was scorched by the ash, which prevented it from producing fruit for a long time, as it does today.Vázquez de Espinosa's account includes the report of the soldier Pedro de Vivar (pp. 470-474) who relates the evolution of the effects of the eruption on Arequipa. According to Pedro de Vivar, in the first days, the population did not know that the rain of ash that plunged the city into darkness had been caused by the eruption of the volcano. Although some already suspected that it might have been caused by the neighbouring volcano, at first, the population considered other possibilities: that it had been caused by the sea or that it was the end of the world. Vivar's account goes into detail on the processions that took place, in which various images were exhibited, such as those of Christ, Santa Marta (advocate for the earthquakes in Arequipa), San Jacinto, San Francisco, Nuestra Señora de Copacabana, del Rosario, de Gracia and de la Consolación, as well as various relics. The soldier details the reaction of the Indians: some offered human sacrifices to the volcano, which Vivar identifies as the devil, and others decided to hang themselves, convinced by the devil. Likewise, the author of the account also points out the prominence of the religious ord