M-1600-HU-08E1	Cabredo, Rodrigo de	Acquaviva, Claudio	Spanish	Cabredo, in his annual letter to the General, recounts the events of the last year in the college of Arequipa and dwells on the effects of the Eruption on the population. Among them, the help given by the Jesuits to the population, the penitences and processions organised, and the consequences on agriculture and geography. He describes the natural causes of the Eruption, as well as its empirical effects (types of thunder, mudslides, landslides, etc.). Special attention is given to the indigenous peoples and their sorcerers, in particular to the way in which those who continued to practise their cults reacted. He also refers to how their diabolical divinities would have decided to punish those Indians who had abandoned their religion to embrace Christian	https://archive.org/details/Mhsi120	Rome, Archivum Romanum Societatis Jesu, Perú 12, ff. 188-226v	1601		clif1en6r0007o3mczespm49j	clif1en6r000jo3mcf6cst4d7	clilwaoiq0047o3nu8ro041pe
M-1600-HU-08E4	Cabredo, Rodrigo de	Acquaviva, Claudio	Spanish	Cabredo informs the General that the harmful effects of the Eruption continue on the crops of Arequipa. He assures him that the preaching of the Jesuits has attributed the cause of the disaster to God's punishment and that its cessation will only come with the collaboration between secular and ecclesiastical justice in the denunciation of sinners and the exiling of the scandalous. But the hand of the devil would have prevented this collaboration from taking place. The devil himself was the cause of the destruction of the Indians who a few days before the Eruption were going to mass to obey the call of their priest. Cabredo also refers to the commemorations held on the day of the disaster (fasting and blood procession) as well as the declaration of San Gennaro as patron saint of the city. The Jesuit prefect was building a church to this saint that the bishop of Cuzco had decided to transform into a parish. Finally, Cabredo claims that the ashes from the Eruption have reached Nueva España, where they have destroyed the cocoa crop, and Tucumán, where they are said to have affected the cotton crop.	https://archive.org/details/Mhsi120	Rome, Archivum Romanum Societatis Jesu, Perù 12, ff. 228-259v	1602		clif1en6r0007o3mczespm49j	clif1en6r000jo3mcf6cst4d7	clilwaoiq0047o3nu8ro041pe
M-1600-HU-0929	Unknown	Acquaviva, Claudio	Spanish	The manuscript containing the account of the college of Arequipa for the year 1600 is the second part of an anonymous History of the Society of Jesus in Peru. The description of the college of Arequipa for 1600 narrates the Eruption of Huaynaputina in February of that year and describes, with slight variations, many of the events referred to in Rodrigo de Cabredo's letter of 30 April 1601 (present in this database).		Rome, Archivum Romanum Societatis Jesu, Perù 26			\N	clif1en6r000jo3mcf6cst4d7	clilwaoiq0047o3nu8ro041pe
