M-1619-TR-0850	Cacho de Santillana, Cristóbal	Philip IV	Spanish	Cacho de Santillana informs the king of the Earthquake, since the viceroy had decided to grant aid to the wretched of Trujillo. He specifies the damage suffered by the population (300 people died) and by the houses of the Spaniards and Indians. Those of the Indians were less affected because they were lighter. He affirms that the Earthquake was felt in Lima and that when it happened, from Trujillo the cabildo, the bishop and the corregidor Luis de Esquivel wrote to the authorities in Lima to give notice. News arrived on the 22nd. He praises the action of the said corregidor and requests a mercy for him. Likewise, Cacho de Santillana affirms that Trujillo requested to change the location of the city and Indians to facilitate its reconstruction. After a meeting of the Audiencia, Cacho de Santillana states that he met with the viceroy to tell him that in a similar event, Arequipa had been helped by granting it Indians and tax exemptions. The viceroy decided to grant Trujillo 10,000 ducats of which 4,000 were to be given as alms to the nuns. He refers to the letter he had already sent to the king in 1610 on the occasion of an Earthquake in Lima in which he warned of the need to remedy the Earthquakes by constructing low buildings and opening wells. But he assures us that the viceroys forget these suggestions when the danger has passed. He ends by referring to some prodigies that preceded the Earthquake.		Seville, Archivo General de Indias, LIMA, 96	1619		clif1en6r0007o3mczespm49j	clif1en6r000ko3mciyg8p705	clilwaozd005mo3nu6akcuob3
